Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Barclays Kenya, Rogers, Sun Resorts

-- B y   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y   a n d   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r
-- 
2011-02-22T14:22:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-22/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-barclays-kenya-rogers-sun-resorts.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped two
days of declines, rising 0.3 percent to 77.05 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index retreated for a fifth day, losing
1 percent to 2,034.75 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis.
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index climbed for a fourth
day, adding 0.1 percent to 26,746.8 by 2:34 p.m. in Lagos. The
Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index increased less than 0.1
percent to 1,044.58 by 2:21 p.m. in Accra. Namibia’s
FTSE  Namibia Overall Index  was little changed at 906.96 by 3:40
p.m. in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Barclays Bank of Kenya Ltd . (BCBL KN), the country’s
second-biggest lender, surged the most since January 2007,
adding 6 shillings, or 9.6 percent, to 68.5 shillings. Profit
jumped 74 percent to 10.6 billion shillings ($129.4 million) in
the 12 months through December from 6.09 billion shillings on
the sale of its custody business and increased loans.  Rogers & Co. (ROGERS MP), Mauritius’s largest diversified
company with 17.7 percent stake in New Mauritius Hotels Ltd.,
the country’s biggest hotel operator, dropped the most in nine
months, retreating 10 rupees, or 3.2 percent, to 305 rupees. Sun
Resorts Ltd. (SUN MP), the second-largest hotel operator, said
full-year profit declined 36 percent to 230.2 million rupees
($7.9 million).  “Investors took cognizance of Sun Resorts’ figures,” Roshan
Ramoly, managing director of the Port Louis-based CIM
Stockbrokers Ltd., said in a phone interview today. Sun fell the
most in two weeks, losing 0.5 rupee, to 0.8 percent, to 60
rupees.  To contact the reporters on this story:
